You need two Shell features: **navigation guards** and **BackButtonBehavior**. Here's a complete implementation:

### 1. Custom "Cancel" back button on `EditProductPage`

```xml
<!-- EditProductPage.xaml -->
<ContentPage xmlns="http://schemas.microsoft.com/dotnet/2021/maui"
             xmlns:x="http://schemas.microsoft.com/winfx/2009/xaml"
             x:Class="MyApp.Views.EditProductPage">

    <Shell.BackButtonBehavior>
        <BackButtonBehavior TextOverride="Cancel"
                           Command="{Binding CancelCommand}" />
    </Shell.BackButtonBehavior>

    <!-- your form content -->
</ContentPage>
```

### 2. ViewModel with cancel logic

```csharp
public partial class EditProductViewModel : ObservableObject
{
    [ObservableProperty]
    bool hasUnsavedChanges;

    [RelayCommand]
    async Task Cancel()
    {
        if (HasUnsavedChanges)
        {
            bool discard = await Shell.Current.DisplayAlert(
                "Unsaved Changes",
                "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
                "Discard", "Stay");

            if (!discard) return;
        }

        await Shell.Current.GoToAsync("..");
    }
}
```

### 3. Guard the hardware/swipe back in `AppShell`

The custom button handles taps, but the user can also swipe back or press the hardware back button. Guard that in `AppShell.xaml.cs`:

```csharp
public partial class AppShell : Shell
{
    public AppShell()
    {
        InitializeComponent();
        Routing.RegisterRoute("editproduct", typeof(EditProductPage));
    }

    protected override async void OnNavigating(ShellNavigatingEventArgs args)
    {
        base.OnNavigating(args);

        // Only intercept back (pop) navigation
        if (args.Source != ShellNavigationSource.Pop)
            return;

        // Only guard the edit page
        if (CurrentPage is not EditProductPage page)
            return;

        var vm = page.BindingContext as EditProductViewModel;
        if (vm is not { HasUnsavedChanges: true })
            return;

        // Pause navigation while we show the dialog
        var deferral = args.GetDeferral();

        bool discard = await DisplayAlert(
            "Unsaved Changes",
            "You have unsaved changes. Discard them?",
            "Discard", "Stay");

        if (!discard)
            args.Cancel();   // user chose "Stay" → block navigation

        deferral.Complete(); // always call this to resume the pipeline
    }
}
```

### How it works

| Scenario | What fires |
|---|---|
| User taps **Cancel** button | `BackButtonBehavior.Command` → ViewModel handles it |
| User swipes back / hardware back | `OnNavigating` guard → deferral + confirmation dialog |

**Key points:**
- `GetDeferral()` is required because `DisplayAlert` is async — without it the navigation completes before the dialog returns.
- Always call `deferral.Complete()` whether you cancel or allow, otherwise navigation freezes.
- The `BackButtonBehavior.Command` **replaces** the default back action, so your ViewModel must call `GoToAsync("..")` explicitly to navigate.
